@misc{Roy2022,
   abstract = {13 Despite decades of study of high-temperature weakly-collisional plasmas, a complete understanding 14 of how energy is transferred between particles and fields in turbulent plasmas remains elusive. Two 15 major questions in this regard are how fluid-scale energy transfer rates, associated with turbulence, 16 connect with kinetic-scale dissipation, and what controls the fraction of dissipation on different charged 17 species. Although the rate of cascade has long been recognized as a limiting factor in the heating rate at 18 kinetic scales, there has not been direct evidence correlating the heating rate with MHD-scale cascade 19 rates. Using kinetic simulations and in-situ spacecraft data, we show that the fluid-scale energy flux 20 indeed accounts for the total energy dissipated at kinetic scales. A phenomenology, based on disruption 21 of proton gyromotion by fluctuating electric fields that are produced in turbulence at proton scales, 22 argues that the proton versus electron heating is controlled by the ratio of the non-linear time scale 23 to the proton-cyclotron time and by the plasma beta. The proposed scalings are supported by the 24 simulations and observations. 25},
