   year = {2020},
}
@article{Gross2015,
   abstract = {Students attending the Center for Integrated Space Weather Modeling (CISM) summer school [Simpson, 2004; Gross et al., 2009] not only ask questions of the lecturers but also submit written questions at the end of each lecture sessions. Over the last decade we have collected approximately 3000 of these submitted questions about space weather and associated physical processes. This article addresses questions commonly asked about magnetic reconnection. Some of the questions are about points that are unclear, while others illuminate how students process new or reprocess previous information and sometimes form common misconceptions about reconnection. Some of these issues arise when students apply conceptual plasma approximations (e.g., "frozen-in-flux" or "particles trapped on field lines") and apply them inappropriately. Another source of student misconceptions is the use of the term reconnection by researchers to describe both the process that reconnects the magnetic field at the reconnection point and also the results of field reconfiguration-accelerated and heated plasmas, high-energy particles, and X-rays emissions. Students may also interpret the standard schematic drawing of X-point reconnection literally, believing that reconnection is confined to a plane, and they often misinterpret the relevant length scales. In addition, student questions indicate that they treat field lines, rather than the fields themselves, as physical objects. The questions below are composite questions gleaned from review of the actual questions that students asked during more than a decade of summer schools. Along with identifying the questions, the aim of this article is to document the responses and provide a few useful references for instructors and students. Rather than a scholarly review of the subject, this manuscript provides succinct answers to common questions about magnetic reconnection. What Is Magnetic Reconnection? The CISM summer school curriculum is at the introductory graduate level and assumes that the participants have not had extensive exposure to plasma physics or space physics concepts. Here is a brief working definition of reconnection used in the CISM summer school. In the low-density plasmas found in space, interparticle collisions are so infrequent that to a very good approximation particles remain on (or are essentially "tied to") a magnetic field line. In the fluid description, the conductivity is so large that fluid elements are tied to or "frozen to" the magnetic field; hence, this approximation is referred to as "frozen-in-flux" wherein the magnetic field is frozen to and moves with the fluid. Magnetic reconnection is a process in which the frozen-influx approximation breaks down, which happens when the magnetic field has large gradients over short enough distances for dissipation or kinetic (nonfluid) effects to become important. Then in a small volume called the diffusion region, field lines can "break" and "reconnect" in a new way. This magnetic reconnection process allows these stressed magnetic fields to relax, which releases magnetic energy that can accelerate and heat the plasma and accelerate a van-ishingly small fraction of particles to high energy. On the large scale these stressed fields are usually the result of plasma flows, even though the onset of reconnection itself may not be the caused by a flow. The term magnetic reconnection is used differently in different contexts, which leads to understandable confusion. At its core, magnetic reconnection is the process by which magnetic field lines change their connectivity. This process creates a new magnetic geometry that is often out of equilibrium. As this field reconfigures, it leads to plasma heating and/or acceleration of plasma flows at the expense of magnetic energy as the field relaxes. Some experts use the term "magnetic reconnection" to include the heating and accelerating processes, (e.g., "the flows are accelerated by magnetic reconnection"), whereas the heating and acceleration can be thought of as consequences of the reconnection process itself. The process that allows the field lines to reconnect does not itself cause most of the heating and accelerated flows, though it can accelerate a small fraction of particles. Reconnection in this narrow sense happens in a very small region called the diffusion region because only in this small region is the plasma not tied to the field line, allowing the magnetic field to "diffuse" through the plasma. A negligible fraction, almost none, of the particles or plasma affected by the reconnection enters the diffusion region. Over a much larger region the particles are accelerated (and in the fluid picture the plasma is heated and flows accelerated) by the reconfiguring of the magnetic field that results from the reconnection.},
   author = {Nicholas A. Gross and W. Jeffrey Hughes},
   doi = {10.1002/2015SW001220},
